        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Due to the redshift the expected sky frequency of the HeH+ line is about 353 GHz and the sky frequency of the CO(18-17) line is about 363 GHz. The lines can be observed simultaneously in the lower and upper sidebands, respectively. The primary beam width at these frequencies is about 17" which allows for simultaneous observations of both source components (their separation is about 4"). We request an angular resolution of 1 arcsec which will be adequate for the detection purpose. 
If we assume the expected line intensity about the same as for our tentative line in SDSS J114816.64+525150.3, the required rms noise for 5sigma detection will be about 1.5 mJy at 50 km/s resolution (the CO and [C II] line widths in this object are about 300 km/s). However we aim at a better sensitivity of 0.5 mJy. It will be adequate for the CO(18-17) line, too. It can be achieved in 1 hour with ALMA, according to the ALMA sensitivity calculator. </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
