    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>One of the most promising molecules for studies of the early Universe is HeH+. Nowadays there is no possibility to search for the HeH+ J=1-0 line with sufficient spectral resolution in the local Universe. A rather high abundance of HeH+ can be expected in dense clouds near distant quasars. Recently we have obtained a tentative detection of an emission line in the spectrum of a northern QSO at z=6.4 which can be attributed to HeH+. Now our goal is to search with much higher sensitivity for the HeH+ line in quasars accessible by ALMA. As a suitable target we select the optically bright and well studied QSO BR 1202-0725 at z=4.7. Its emission is resolved into two components, one at the location of the QSO and the other ~ 4" northwest. These components may represent a pair of interacting galaxies. X-ray emission detected from the southern component and, at 99.6% confidence level, from the northern component can create favourable conditions for HeH+ formation as well as for excitation of high-J CO transitions. We propose to search simultaneously for the HeH+ J=1-0 and CO J=18-17 lines and wish to emphasize that even upper limits would be relevant.</prp:abstract>
